% You are an expert Python engineer. Your goal is to write the pdd/cli_detector.py module.

% Role & Scope
Detects and bootstraps agentic CLI harnesses (Claude CLI, Codex CLI, Gemini CLI, OpenCode CLI) required for `pdd fix`, `pdd change`, `pdd bug`, and `pdd setup`. The primary entry point `detect_and_bootstrap_cli()` presents a numbered table of CLIs with install/configuration status, lets the user select one or more, and walks through installation and provider configuration for each. The legacy `detect_cli_tools()` function is preserved for backward compatibility.

% Requirements

1. Dataclass: `CliBootstrapResult` with fields `cli_name: str`, `provider: str`, `cli_path: str`, `api_key_configured: bool`, `skipped: bool` (default False). All strings default to empty.

2. Function: `detect_and_bootstrap_cli() -> List[CliBootstrapResult]` — Phase 1 entry point for `pdd setup`.
   a. Print a step banner via `_print_step_banner()` imported from `pdd.setup_tool`.
   b. Detect all four CLIs via `shutil.which()` with fallback to common paths (~/.npm-global/bin, ~/.local/bin, ~/bin, /usr/local/bin, /opt/homebrew/bin, /home/linuxbrew/.linuxbrew/bin) and nvm node version directories.
   c. Provider mappings: anthropic->claude, openai->codex, google->gemini, opencode->opencode. Table order: Claude CLI, Codex CLI, Gemini CLI, OpenCode CLI.
   d. Print a numbered selection table showing install status and configuration status per CLI, with aligned columns.
   e. Accept comma-separated numeric input (e.g. "1,4"). Default to best available (installed+configured > installed > Claude). "q"/"n" returns a skipped result.
   f. For each selected CLI, process install/key/test in sequence. On skip or failure of one CLI, continue to the next.
   g. Install step: prompt user, run `npm install -g ...` via subprocess if accepted. Check npm availability first. OpenCode install command is `npm install -g opencode-ai`; if npm is unavailable, print alternate guidance: `curl -fsSL https://opencode.ai/install | bash` or `brew install anomalyco/tap/opencode`.
   h. Configuration step: API-key providers prompt for a key, save to `~/.pdd/api-env.{shell}` with shell-appropriate syntax, add source line to RC file, and set in `os.environ`. OpenCode does not use a PDD-managed API key; check `OPENCODE_MODEL` as its primary configuration signal, recommend an explicit `provider/model` value, offer to save it to `~/.pdd/api-env.{shell}`, and print `opencode auth login` plus `opencode models` guidance. Also display `OPENCODE_AGENT`, `OPENCODE_VARIANT`, and optional `PDD_OPENCODE_MODE` when set.
   i. CLI test step (always runs, cannot be skipped): run `cli --version`, fall back to `--help` if that fails. Treat a selected OpenCode CLI as usable only when one of those commands completes successfully.
   j. Handle KeyboardInterrupt/EOFError at every input prompt gracefully.
   k. Return list of results; if empty, return `[CliBootstrapResult(skipped=True)]`.

3. Function: `detect_cli_tools() -> None` — legacy detection. For each CLI: show found/not-found status, cross-reference API keys or OpenCode configuration, offer installation for missing CLIs that have matching provider configuration.

4. Shell detection: detect from `SHELL` env var (default "bash"). Map to RC file: zsh->.zshrc, bash->.bashrc, fish->~/.config/fish/config.fish.

5. API key file management: create `~/.pdd/` if needed. Write keys to `~/.pdd/api-env.{shell}` (append, dedup by key name using regex). Add source line to RC file if not present. Shell syntax: bash/zsh use `export K=V`, fish uses `set -gx K V`. Source syntax: bash/zsh use `source path`, fish uses `test -f path ; and source path`.

6. Google provider: primary env var is GEMINI_API_KEY (used by Gemini CLI for AI Studio auth). Fallback is GOOGLE_API_KEY (Vertex AI convention). Check GEMINI_API_KEY first, then GOOGLE_API_KEY. Primary key for saving is GEMINI_API_KEY. Display whichever is actually set.

7. OpenCode provider: primary configuration env var is `OPENCODE_MODEL` and recommended value format is `provider/model`. Missing `OPENCODE_MODEL` should produce a yellow warning explaining that OpenCode default-model resolution can hang or fail; it should not trigger an API-key prompt. Support optional `OPENCODE_AGENT`, `OPENCODE_VARIANT`, and `PDD_OPENCODE_MODE` as pass-through configuration shown in setup messaging.

8. Module-level constants: `PROVIDER_PRIMARY_KEY`, `PROVIDER_DISPLAY`, `CLI_PREFERENCE`, `SHELL_RC_MAP` exposed for use by other modules.

% Dependencies

